	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>The challenge of regional integration in Southern and Eastern Africa </h1>

			
			<h4>
												07 May 2012
										</h4>

						<h2>An interview with Rob Davies, South African Minister of Trade and Industry</h2>
					</header>


				<div class="intro">

						
<div class="object-left">		
<div class="embed-image">
<img border="0" src="/var/agritrade/storage/images/south-african-trade-and-industry-minister-rob-davies/692720-1-eng-GB/South-African-Trade-and-Industry-Minister-Rob-Davies_small.jpg" width="54" height="70"></div></div><p>Rob Davies is South Africa's Minister of Trade and Industry. He previously served as Deputy Minister of Trade and Industry, and Chairman of the Parliamentary Portfolio Committee on Finance. Prior to entering Parliament in 1994, Rob Davies was Professor and Co-Director of the Centre for Southern African Studies at the University of the Western Cape, and previously the Centre for African Studies at the Eduardo Mondlane University in Mozambique, where he researched and wrote extensively on regional economic integration issues.</p>

		</div>
		
		
					<p><b>Q: Does the need for balanced and equitable regional development inform the South African government’s approach to regional agricultural trade negotiations?</b></p><p>Certainly, the development integration approach to regional trade negotiations has been firmly accepted by the heads of state involved in the tripartite Free-Trade Area (T-FTA) negotiations (of SADC, COMESA and the EAC). This recognises that in developing regions like ours, many of the most important barriers to promoting equitable, mutually beneficial trade are not tariffs, but inadequate infrastructure and underdeveloped production bases. Hence, we will combine the FTA with cooperation to build infrastructure and develop productive capacity.</p><p>As far as the FTA policy is concerned, we will also build this on principles of asymmetry and differentiation, recognising that trade liberalisation within an FTA could, in our context, result in a polarisation of economic development to the benefit of the stronger economies.</p><p>Ministers across Africa have recognised the importance of having a strong industrial pillar to regional integration initiatives. Currently this focuses on three main areas: mineral beneficiation, development of pharmaceutical industries, and development of agro-processing industries.</p><p><b>&nbsp;</b></p><p><b>Q: Given the existing use of agricultural trade policy tools in the SACU and SADC context, what approach do you envisage being adopted to their use in the T-FTA context?</b></p><p>At the moment the discussions have largely focused on the broad principles of the approach to be adopted. Our approach as South Africa is to recognise each other’s sensitivities and the centrality of industrial development objectives, and to use this to forge a development integration approach.</p><p>In terms of the use of agricultural trade policy tools, this debate still has to take place. We are very far away at this stage from any specific details on the use of trade policy tools and the tariff treatment to be accorded particular products. This will need to be dealt with on a product-by-product basis, in close consultation with the Ministry of Agriculture and concerned industry stakeholders.</p><p>In South Africa, this means that the Department of Trade and Industry (DTI<b>)</b> will take its lead from the Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries on agricultural tariff discussions, in the context of the deliberations which will need to take place in the National Economic Development and Labour Council (Nedlac). In other countries of the T-FTA there may be capacity constraints on the ability of agricultural ministries to engage with trade policy issues, but this is an issue we don’t have to confront in South Africa.</p><p>What is clear at this stage is that we are aiming at a process which recognises the different development needs of member countries on the basis of their existing production and trade policy realities. The focus must be on what can be achieved in practice. Hence, the importance attached in the past 6 months to information sharing.</p><p>In order to address the sensitivities of different countries – and we all have sensitivities – we need to know what they are. There needs to be a frank recognition of national sensitivities, with ways being found to work around these sensitivities.</p><p><b>&nbsp;</b></p><p><b>Q: Do you envisage the T-FTA negotiations having implications for the use of existing agricultural trade policy tools within the SACU and the SADC?</b></p><p>Our approach to the T-FTA process is that we should not seek to renegotiate the SADC FTA, or the COMESA or EAC arrangements among existing members, but rather to extend the benefits applicable within each of the three regions across the broader T-FTA area.</p><p>This being said, in the SADC we are about to hit a moment of truth, given the commitment in the Regional Indicative Strategic Development Programme to moving from the liberalisation of ‘substantially all trade’ to full trade liberalisation within the SADC FTA. This is going to come up against some powerful realities. Some member states are behind even in the implementation of their existing tariff reduction commitments. Other member states have granted the tariff concessions, but then implemented new regulatory measures which undermine the tariff benefits granted.</p><p><b>&nbsp;</b></p><p><b>Q: In this context, what lessons do you feel can be drawn from this SACU and SADC experience for the T-FTA process?</b></p><p>Well, there is some leeway under the SACU for seasonal arrangements for trade in agricultural products, and this is not under any challenge in SACU.</p><p>In terms of the use of tariff-rate quotas in the SADC context, and whether this could be extended, it’s far too early in the process for any precision on these issues.</p><p>The important thing is to recognise the realities of local production bases, identify complementarities, and build on these in terms of the policies and policy tools adopted.</p><p>Let me stress, however, it’s too early for any specific details. At this stage it’s about the broad approach.</p><p><b>&nbsp;</b></p><p><b>Q: In this context, the draft T-FTA proposals prepared by the regional secretariats appear to focus on a broad-stroke liberalisation approach ...</b></p><p>These proposals are a starting point. The trilateral negotiations will be a member-driven process. This is particularly important for SADC and COMESA members, given the overlapping membership of these bodies. What we insist is that when it comes to the details of tariff concessions and the use of trade policy tools, this will be the outcome of negotiations and will not be outsourced by member governments.</p><p>What we will need to confront, both within our RECs (Regional Economic Communities) as well as perhaps at the T-FTA level, will be inconsistencies. This manifests itself sometimes in calls for very ambitious trade liberalisation commitments followed by non-implementation or the adoption of other regulatory measures which undermine the effects of liberalisation commitments made. This situation needs to be clarified based on a frank exchange on current production realities and concerns. Once these are understood, the focus can be on developing a realistic level of ambition based, in our view, on identifying complementarities, including in the priority area of the agro-processing sector.</p><p><b>&nbsp;</b></p><p><b>Q: Within the T-FTA process do you see any need for flanking policies, for example with regard to regional competition policy?</b></p><p>Currently, many of our countries don’t even have competition policies at national level. In South Africa, we actively use competition policy to prevent abuse in the marketplace (for example on bread). While not currently on the agenda of the T-FTA negotiations, we would not want to see South African firms engaged in anti-competitive behaviour elsewhere on the continent.</p>
		
		
		
		
		
